\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Now Abraham again took a wife, and her name was Keturah. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0In time she bore him Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.\
\cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Jokshan became father to Sheba and Dedan.\
The sons of Dedan were Asshurim, Letushim, and Leummim.\
\cf4 4\cf5 \'a0The sons of Midian were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah.\
All of these were the sons of Keturah.\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0Later on Abraham gave everything he had to Isaac, \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0but Abraham gave gifts to his sons by his concubines. Then while he was still alive, he sent them eastward, away from Isaac his son, to the land of the East. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0The years of Abraham\'92s life were 175 years. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0Then Abraham breathed his last and died at a good old age, old and satisfied, and was gathered to his people. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0His sons Isaac and Ishmael buried him in the cave of Machpelah in the field of Ephron the son of Zohar the Hittite that is in front of Mamre, \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0the field that Abraham had purchased from the sons of Heth. There Abraham was buried, with his wife Sarah. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0After Abraham\'92s death, God continued to bless his son Isaac, and Isaac was dwelling near Beer-lahai-roi.\
\cf4 12\cf5 \'a0This is the history of Ishmael the son of Abraham whom Hagar the Egyptian, the servant of Sarah, bore to Abraham.\
\cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Now these are the names of the sons of Ishmael, by their names according to their family origins: Ishmael\'92s firstborn Nebaioth, then Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0Mishma, Dumah, Massa, \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah. \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0These are the sons of Ishmael, and these are their names by their settlements and by their encampments, 12 chieftains according to their clans. \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0And Ishmael lived for 137 years. Then he breathed his last and died and was gathered to his people. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0And they took up dwelling from Havilah near Shur, which is close to Egypt, as far as Assyria. He settled near all his brothers.\
\cf4 19\cf5 \'a0And this is the history of Isaac the son of Abraham.\
Abraham became father to Isaac. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Isaac was 40 years old when he married Rebekah, the daughter of Bethuel the Aramaean of Paddan-aram, the sister of Laban the Aramaean. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0And Isaac kept pleading with Jehovah regarding his wife, because she was barren; so Jehovah responded to his plea, and his wife Rebekah became pregnant. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0And the sons within her began to struggle with each other, so that she said: \'93If this is the way it is, why should I go on living?\'94 So she inquired of Jehovah. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0And Jehovah said to her: \'93Two nations are in your womb, and two peoples will be separated from within you; and the one nation will be stronger than the other nation, and the older will serve the younger.\'94\
\cf4 24\cf5 \'a0When the time came for her to give birth, look! twins were in her womb. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Then the first came out red all over and was like a garment of hair, so they named him Esau. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0After that his brother came out and his hand was holding onto the heel of Esau, so he named him Jacob. Isaac was 60 years old when she gave birth to them.\
\cf4 27\cf5 \'a0As the boys got bigger, Esau became a skilled hunter, a man of the field, but Jacob was a blameless man, dwelling in tents. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0And Isaac loved Esau because it meant game in his mouth, whereas Rebekah loved Jacob. \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0On one occasion Jacob was boiling some stew when Esau returned from the field exhausted. \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0So Esau said to Jacob: \'93Quick, please, give me some of the red stew that you have there, for I am exhausted!\'94 That is why his name was Edom. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0To this Jacob said: \'93First sell me your right as firstborn!\'94 \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0And Esau continued: \'93Here I am about to die! What use is a birthright to me?\'94 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0And Jacob added: \'93Swear to me first!\'94 So he swore to him and sold his right as firstborn to Jacob. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob gave Esau bread and lentil stew, and he ate and drank, and he got up and went away. Thus Esau despised the birthright.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

