\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Now there was a famine in the land, in addition to the first famine that occurred in the days of Abraham, so that Isaac went to Abimelech king of the Philistines, in Gerar. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0Then Jehovah appeared to him and said: \'93Do not go down to Egypt. Dwell in the land that I designate to you. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Reside as a foreigner in this land, and I will continue with you and bless you because to you and to your offspring I will give all these lands, and I will carry out the oath that I swore to your father Abraham: \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0\'91I will multiply your offspring like the stars of the heavens; and I will give to your offspring all these lands; and by means of your offspring, all nations of the earth will obtain a blessing for themselves,\'92 \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0on account of the fact that Abraham listened to my voice and continued to keep my requirements, my commands, my statutes, and my laws.\'94 \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0So Isaac continued to dwell in Gerar.\
\cf4 7\cf5 \'a0When the men of the place kept asking about his wife, he would say: \'93She is my sister.\'94 He was afraid to say, \'93She is my wife,\'94 for he said, \'93The men of the place might kill me because of Rebekah,\'94 for she was beautiful in appearance. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0After some time had passed, Abimelech king of the Philistines was looking out of the window, and he saw Isaac displaying affection for Rebekah his wife. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0At once Abimelech called Isaac and said: \'93She is actually your wife! Why did you say, \'91She is my sister\'92?\'94 At this Isaac said to him: \'93I said it for fear I should die because of her.\'94 \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0But Abimelech continued: \'93What have you done to us? One of the people could easily have lain down with your wife, and you would have brought guilt upon us!\'94 \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Then Abimelech commanded all the people, saying: \'93Anybody touching this man and his wife will surely be put to death!\'94\
\cf4 12\cf5 \'a0And Isaac began to sow seed in that land, and in that year he reaped 100 times what he sowed, for Jehovah was blessing him. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0The man became wealthy, and he continued to prosper until he became very wealthy. \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0He acquired flocks of sheep and herds of cattle and a large body of servants, and the Philistines began to envy him.\
\cf4 15\cf5 \'a0So the Philistines took soil and stopped up all the wells that his father\'92s servants had dug in the days of Abraham. \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0Abimelech then said to Isaac: \'93Move from our neighborhood, for you have grown far stronger than we are.\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0So Isaac moved from there and encamped in the valley of Gerar and began dwelling there. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0And Isaac again dug the wells that had been dug in the days of his father Abraham but that the Philistines had stopped up after Abraham\'92s death, and he called them by the names that his father had given them.\
\cf4 19\cf5 \'a0When the servants of Isaac were digging in the valley, they found a well of fresh water. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0And the shepherds of Gerar began quarreling with the shepherds of Isaac, saying: \'93The water is ours!\'94 So he named the well Esek, because they had quarreled with him. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0And they started digging another well, and they began quarreling over it also. So he named it Sitnah. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0Later he moved away from there and dug another well, but they did not quarrel over it. So he named it Rehoboth and said: \'93It is because now Jehovah has given us ample room and has made us fruitful in the land.\'94\
\cf4 23\cf5 \'a0Then he went up from there to Beer-sheba. \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0That night Jehovah appeared to him and said: \'93I am the God of your father Abraham. Do not be afraid, for I am with you, and I will bless you and multiply your offspring on account of Abraham my servant.\'94 \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0So he built an altar there and called on the name of Jehovah. And Isaac pitched his tent there, and his servants dug a well there.\
\cf4 26\cf5 \'a0Later Abimelech came to him from Gerar with Ahuzzath his personal adviser and Phicol the chief of his army. \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0At this Isaac said to them: \'93Why have you come to me, seeing that you hated me and sent me away from your neighborhood?\'94 \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0To this they said: \'93We have clearly seen that Jehovah has been with you. So we said, \'91Let there, please, be an oath of obligation between us and you, and let us make a covenant with you \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0that you will do nothing bad to us just as we have not harmed you, seeing that we have done only good to you in that we sent you away in peace. You now are the blessed of Jehovah.\'92\'94 \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0Then he made a feast for them, and they ate and drank. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0In the morning they got up early and swore an oath to each other. After that Isaac sent them away, and they went from him in peace.\
\cf4 32\cf5 \'a0On that day the servants of Isaac came and reported to him about the well that they had dug, and they told him: \'93We have found water!\'94 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0So he named it Shibah. That is why the name of the city is Beer-sheba to this day.\
\cf4 34\cf5 \'a0When Esau was 40 years old, he took as wife Judith the daughter of Beeri the Hittite and also Basemath the daughter of Elon the Hittite. \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0They were a source of great grief to Isaac and Rebekah.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

