\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Now when Isaac was old and his eyes were too weak to see, he called Esau his older son to him and said: \'93My son!\'94 He replied: \'93Here I am!\'94 \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0And he went on to say: \'93I have now grown old. I do not know the day of my death. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0So at this time take, please, your weapons, your quiver and your bow, and go out to the field and hunt some wild game for me. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0Then make the kind of tasty dish that I am fond of and bring it to me. Then I will eat it so that I may bless you before I die.\'94\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0However, Rebekah was listening while Isaac spoke to Esau his son. And Esau went out into the field to hunt game and to bring it in. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0And Rebekah said to Jacob her son: \'93I just heard your father speaking to your brother Esau, saying, \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0\'91Bring me some game and make me a tasty dish. Then let me eat so that I may bless you before Jehovah before my death.\'92 \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0And now, my son, listen carefully and do what I am instructing you. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0Go, please, to the herd and get me two of the best young goats from there so that I may prepare from them a tasty dish for your father, just the way he likes it. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0Then take it to your father to eat, in order that he may bless you before his death.\'94\
\cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Jacob said to his mother Rebekah: \'93But Esau my brother is a hairy man, and my skin is smooth. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0What if my father feels me? Then I will certainly appear to be mocking him, and I will bring upon myself a curse rather than a blessing.\'94 \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0At this his mother said to him: \'93Upon me be the curse meant for you, my son. Just do as I say and go, get them for me.\'94 \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0So he went and got them and brought them to his mother, and his mother made a tasty dish, just the way his father liked it. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0After that Rebekah took her older son Esau\'92s finest garments, which she had in the house, and put them on her younger son Jacob. \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0She also put the skins of the young goats on his hands and on the hairless part of his neck. \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0Then she handed the tasty dish and the bread that she had made to her son Jacob.\
\cf4 18\cf5 \'a0So he went in to his father and said: \'93My father!\'94 to which he said: \'93Here I am! Who are you, my son?\'94 \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0Jacob said to his father: \'93I am Esau your firstborn. I have done just as you told me. Sit up, please, and eat some of my game, so that you may bless me.\'94 \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0At that Isaac said to his son: \'93How were you so quick in finding it, my son?\'94 He replied: \'93Because Jehovah your God brought it to me.\'94 \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0Then Isaac said to Jacob: \'93Come near, please, that I may feel you, my son, to know whether you are really my son Esau or not.\'94 \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0So Jacob came near to his father Isaac, and he felt him, after which he said: \'93The voice is the voice of Jacob, but the hands are the hands of Esau.\'94 \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0He did not recognize him because his hands were hairy like the hands of his brother Esau. So he blessed him.\
\cf4 24\cf5 \'a0After that he asked: \'93Are you really my son Esau?\'94 to which he replied: \'93I am.\'94 \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Then he said: \'93Bring me some of the wild game for me to eat, my son, then I will bless you.\'94 With that he brought it to him and he ate, and he brought him wine and he drank. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0Then Isaac his father said to him: \'93Come near, please, and kiss me, my son.\'94 \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0So he came near and kissed him, and he could smell the scent of his garments. Then he blessed him and said:\
\'93See, the scent of my son is like the scent of the field that Jehovah has blessed. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0May the true God give you the dews of the heavens and the fertile soils of the earth and an abundance of grain and new wine. \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0Let peoples serve you, and let nations bow low to you. Be master over your brothers, and let the sons of your mother bow low to you. Cursed be everyone who curses you, and blessed be everyone who blesses you.\'94\
\cf4 30\cf5 \'a0Now Isaac had just finished blessing Jacob, and Jacob had barely left the presence of his father Isaac when his brother Esau came back from his hunting. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0He too prepared a tasty dish and brought it to his father, and he said to his father: \'93Let my father get up and eat some of his son\'92s game, in order that you may bless me.\'94 \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0At this his father Isaac said to him: \'93Who are you?\'94 to which he said: \'93I am your son, your firstborn, Esau.\'94 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0And Isaac began to tremble violently, so he said: \'93Who was it, then, who hunted for game and brought it to me? I already ate it before you arrived, and I blessed him\'97and he will surely be blessed!\'94\
\cf4 34\cf5 \'a0On hearing his father\'92s words, Esau began to cry out in an extremely loud and bitter manner and to say to his father: \'93Bless me, yes, me too, my father!\'94 \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0But he said: \'93Your brother came deceitfully so that he might get the blessing meant for you.\'94 \cf4 36\cf5 \'a0At this he said: \'93Is he not rightly named Jacob, that he might supplant me these two times? My birthright he has already taken, and now he has taken my blessing!\'94 Then he added: \'93Have you not reserved a blessing for me?\'94 \cf4 37\cf5 \'a0But Isaac answered Esau: \'93Here I have appointed him master over you, and I have given him all his brothers as servants, and I have bestowed grain and new wine for his support. What is left that I can do for you, my son?\'94\
\cf4 38\cf5 \'a0Esau said to his father: \'93Is there just one blessing that you have, my father? Bless me, yes, me too, my father!\'94 With that Esau cried loudly and burst into tears. \cf4 39\cf5 \'a0So his father Isaac answered him:\
\'93See, away from the fertile soils of the earth your dwelling will be, and away from the dew of the heavens above. \cf4 40\cf5 \'a0And by your sword you will live, and you will serve your brother. But when you grow restless, you will indeed break his yoke off your neck.\'94\
\cf4 41\cf5 \'a0However, Esau harbored animosity against Jacob because of the blessing his father had given him, and Esau kept saying in his heart: \'93The days of mourning for my father are getting closer. After that I am going to kill Jacob my brother.\'94 \cf4 42\cf5 \'a0When the words of her older son Esau were told to Rebekah, she at once sent for her younger son Jacob and said to him: \'93Look! Your brother Esau is planning to take revenge by killing you. \cf4 43\cf5 \'a0Now, my son, do as I say. Get up and run away to my brother Laban at Haran. \cf4 44\cf5 \'a0Dwell with him for a while until your brother\'92s rage calms down, \cf4 45\cf5 \'a0until your brother\'92s anger toward you subsides and he forgets what you have done to him. Then I will send for you from there. Why should I lose both of you in one day?\'94\
\cf4 46\cf5 \'a0After that Rebekah kept saying to Isaac: \'93I am disgusted with my life because of the daughters of Heth. If Jacob ever takes a wife from the daughters of Heth, like these daughters of the land, what good is my life?\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

