\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0After that Jacob resumed his journey and traveled on to the land of the people of the East. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0Now he saw a well in the field and three droves of sheep lying down next to it, because they usually watered the droves from that well. There was a large stone over the mouth of the well. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0When all the droves had been gathered there, they rolled away the stone from the mouth of the well, and they watered the flocks, after which they returned the stone to its place over the mouth of the well.\
\cf4 4\cf5 \'a0So Jacob said to them: \'93My brothers, what place are you from?\'94 to which they said: \'93We are from Haran.\'94 \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0He said to them: \'93Do you know Laban the grandson of Nahor?\'94 to which they said: \'93We know him.\'94 \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0At this he said to them: \'93Is he well?\'94 They replied: \'93He is well. And here is his daughter Rachel coming with the sheep!\'94 \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0Then he said: \'93It is still the middle of the day. It is not the time for gathering the herds. Water the sheep, and then go feed them.\'94 \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0To this they said: \'93We are not allowed to do so until all the droves are gathered and they roll the stone away from the mouth of the well. Then we water the sheep.\'94\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0While he was yet speaking with them, Rachel came with her father\'92s sheep, for she was a shepherdess. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0When Jacob saw Rachel, the daughter of Laban his mother\'92s brother, and the sheep of Laban, Jacob immediately approached and rolled the stone away from the mouth of the well and watered the sheep of Laban his mother\'92s brother. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob kissed Rachel and raised his voice and burst into tears. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0And Jacob began to tell Rachel that he was the relative of her father and that he was the son of Rebekah. And she ran off and told her father.\
\cf4 13\cf5 \'a0As soon as Laban heard the report about Jacob the son of his sister, he ran to meet him. He embraced him and kissed him and brought him into his house. And he began to tell Laban all these things. \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0Laban said to him: \'93You are indeed my bone and my flesh.\'94 So he stayed with him a full month.\
\cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Laban then said to Jacob: \'93Just because you are my relative, should you serve me for nothing? Tell me, what are your wages to be?\'94 \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0Now Laban had two daughters. The name of the older was Leah, and the name of the younger, Rachel. \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0But the eyes of Leah had no luster, whereas Rachel had become a very attractive and beautiful woman. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Jacob had fallen in love with Rachel, so he said: \'93I am willing to serve you seven years for your younger daughter Rachel.\'94 \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0To this Laban said: \'93It is better for me to give her to you than to give her to another man. Keep dwelling with me.\'94 \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0And Jacob served seven years for Rachel, but in his eyes they were like just a few days because of his love for her.\
\cf4 21\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob said to Laban: \'93Give over my wife because my days are up, and let me have relations with her.\'94 \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0With that Laban gathered all the men of the place and made a feast. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0But during the evening, he resorted to taking his daughter Leah and bringing her to him that he might have relations with her. \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0Laban also gave his female servant Zilpah to his daughter Leah as a servant. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0In the morning Jacob saw that it was Leah! So he said to Laban: \'93What have you done to me? Was it not for Rachel that I served you? Why have you tricked me?\'94 \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0To this Laban said: \'93It is not our custom here to give the younger woman before the firstborn. \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0Celebrate the week of this woman. After that you will also be given this other woman in exchange for serving me seven more years.\'94 \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0Jacob did so and celebrated the week of this woman, after which he gave him his daughter Rachel as a wife. \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0Besides, Laban gave his female servant Bilhah to his daughter Rachel as her servant.\
\cf4 30\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob had relations also with Rachel, and he loved Rachel more than Leah, and he served him for another seven years. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0When Jehovah saw that Leah was unloved, he then enabled her to become pregnant, but Rachel was barren. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0So Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son and named him Reuben, for she said: \'93It is because Jehovah has looked upon my affliction, for now my husband will begin to love me.\'94 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0And she again became pregnant and gave birth to a son and then said: \'93It is because Jehovah has listened, in that I was unloved, so he gave me this one also.\'94 Then she named him Simeon. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0And she became pregnant yet again and gave birth to a son and then said: \'93Now this time my husband will join himself to me, because I have borne him three sons.\'94 Therefore, he was named Levi. \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0And she became pregnant once more and gave birth to a son and then said: \'93This time I will praise Jehovah.\'94 She therefore named him Judah. After that she stopped giving birth.\
