\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0When Rachel saw that she had borne no children to Jacob, she became jealous of her sister and began to say to Jacob: \'93Give me children or else I will die.\'94 \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0At this Jacob\'92s anger flared up against Rachel, and he said: \'93Am I in the place of God, who has prevented you from having children?\'94 \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0So she said: \'93Here is my slave girl Bilhah. Have relations with her in order that she may bear children for me and that through her, I too may have children.\'94 \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0With that she gave him her servant Bilhah as a wife, and Jacob had relations with her. \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0Bilhah became pregnant and in time bore Jacob a son. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0Then Rachel said: \'93God has acted as my judge and has also listened to my voice, so that he gave me a son.\'94 That is why she named him Dan. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0Bilhah, Rachel\'92s servant, became pregnant once more and in time bore Jacob a second son. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0Then Rachel said: \'93With strenuous wrestlings I have wrestled with my sister. I have also come off the winner!\'94 So she named him Naphtali.\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0When Leah saw that she had stopped having children, she took her servant Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as a wife. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0And Leah\'92s servant Zilpah bore a son to Jacob. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Then Leah said: \'93With good fortune!\'94 So she named him Gad. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0After that Zilpah, Leah\'92s servant, bore a second son to Jacob. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Then Leah said: \'93With my happiness! For the daughters will certainly pronounce me happy.\'94 So she named him Asher.\
\cf4 14\cf5 \'a0Now Reuben was walking in the days of the wheat harvest, and he found mandrakes in the field. So he brought them to his mother Leah. Then Rachel said to Leah: \'93Give me, please, some of your son\'92s mandrakes.\'94 \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0At this she said to her: \'93Is it a small matter that you took my husband? Would you now take my son\'92s mandrakes also?\'94 So Rachel said: \'93Very well. He will lie down with you tonight in exchange for your son\'92s mandrakes.\'94\
\cf4 16\cf5 \'a0When Jacob was coming from the field in the evening, Leah went out to meet him and said: \'93It is with me you are going to have relations, because I have hired you outright with my son\'92s mandrakes.\'94 So he lay down with her that night. \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0And God heard and answered Leah, and she became pregnant and in time bore to Jacob a fifth son. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Then Leah said: \'93God has given me my wages because I have given my servant to my husband.\'94 So she named him Issachar. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0And Leah became pregnant once more and in time bore a sixth son to Jacob. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Then Leah said: \'93God has endowed me, yes, me, with a good endowment. At last, my husband will tolerate me, for I have borne him six sons.\'94 So she named him Zebulun. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0Afterward she bore a daughter and named her Dinah.\
\cf4 22\cf5 \'a0Finally God remembered Rachel, and God heard and answered her by enabling her to become pregnant. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0And she became pregnant and gave birth to a son. Then she said: \'93God has taken away my reproach!\'94 \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0So she named him Joseph, saying: \'93Jehovah is adding another son to me.\'94\
\cf4 25\cf5 \'a0After Rachel had given birth to Joseph, Jacob immediately said to Laban: \'93Send me away so that I may go to my place and to my land. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0Give over my wives and my children, for whom I have served with you, that I may go, for you well know how I have served you.\'94 \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0Then Laban said to him: \'93If I have found favor in your eyes,\'97I have understood by the omens that Jehovah is blessing me because of you.\'94 \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0And he added: \'93Stipulate your wages to me, and I will give them.\'94 \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0So Jacob said to him: \'93You know how I have served you and how your herd has fared with me; \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0you had little before my coming, but your herd has increased and multiplied, and Jehovah has blessed you since I arrived. So when will I do something for my own house?\'94\
\cf4 31\cf5 \'a0Then he said: \'93What should I give you?\'94 And Jacob said: \'93You will give me nothing whatsoever! If you will do this one thing for me, I will resume shepherding your flock and guarding it. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0I will pass through your whole flock today. You set aside from there every sheep speckled and with color patches and every dark-brown sheep among the young rams and any color-patched and speckled one among the she-goats. From now on, these must become my wages. \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0And my righteousness must speak for me on a future day when you come to look over my wages; every one that is not speckled and color-patched among the she-goats and dark brown among the young rams will be considered stolen if it is with me.\'94\
\cf4 34\cf5 \'a0To this Laban said: \'93That is fine! Let it be according to your word.\'94 \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0Then on that day, he set aside the he-goats striped and color-patched and all the she-goats speckled and color-patched, every one in which there was any white and every one dark brown among the young rams, and gave them into the care of his sons. \cf4 36\cf5 \'a0After that he set a distance of three days\'92 journey between himself and Jacob, and Jacob was shepherding the flocks of Laban that remained over.\
\cf4 37\cf5 \'a0Jacob then took freshly cut staffs of the storax, almond, and plane trees, and he peeled white spots in them by exposing the white wood of the staffs. \cf4 38\cf5 \'a0Then he placed the staffs that he had peeled in front of the flock, in the gutters, in the drinking troughs, where the flocks would come to drink, that they might get into heat in front of them when they came to drink.\
\cf4 39\cf5 \'a0So the flocks would get into heat in front of the staffs, and the flocks would produce striped, speckled, and color-patched offspring. \cf4 40\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob separated the young rams and turned the flocks to face the striped ones and all the dark-brown ones among the flocks of Laban. Then he separated his own flocks and did not mix them with Laban\'92s flocks. \cf4 41\cf5 \'a0And whenever the robust animals would get into heat, Jacob would place the staffs in the gutters before the eyes of the flocks, that they might get into heat by the staffs. \cf4 42\cf5 \'a0But when the animals were weak, he would not place the staffs there. So the weak ones always came to be Laban\'92s, but the robust ones became Jacob\'92s.\
\cf4 43\cf5 \'a0And the man grew very prosperous, and he acquired great flocks and male and female servants and camels and donkeys.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

