\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0In time he heard what the sons of Laban were saying: \'93Jacob has taken everything that belonged to our father, and from what belonged to our father, he has amassed all this wealth.\'94 \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0When Jacob would look at the face of Laban, he saw that his attitude toward him was not what it used to be. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Finally Jehovah said to Jacob: \'93Return to the land of your fathers and to your relatives, and I will continue with you.\'94 \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob sent a message to Rachel and Leah to come out to the field to his flock, \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0and he said to them:\
\'93I have seen that your father\'92s attitude toward me has changed, but the God of my father has been with me. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0You yourselves certainly know that I have served your father with all my power. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0And your father has tried to cheat me and has changed my wages ten times; but God has not allowed him to do me harm. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0If on the one hand he would say, \'91The speckled ones will be your wages,\'92 then the whole flock produced speckled ones; but if on the other hand he would say, \'91The striped ones will be your wages,\'92 then the whole flock produced striped ones. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0So God kept taking your father\'92s livestock away from him and giving it to me. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0Once when the flock got into heat, I raised my eyes and saw in a dream that the he-goats mating with the flock were striped, speckled, and spotty. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Then the angel of the true God said to me in the dream, \'91Jacob!\'92 to which I said, \'91Here I am.\'92 \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0And he continued, \'91Raise your eyes, please, and see that all the he-goats mating with the flock are striped, speckled, and spotty, for I have seen all that Laban is doing to you. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0I am the true God of Bethel, where you anointed a pillar and where you made a vow to me. Now get up, go out of this land, and return to the land of your birth.\'92\'94\
\cf4 14\cf5 \'a0At this Rachel and Leah answered him: \'93Is there any share left for us to inherit in our father\'92s house? \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Does he not consider us as foreigners, since he has sold us and has been using up the money given for us? \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0All the riches that God has taken away from our father are ours and our children\'92s. So, then, do everything that God has told you to do.\'94\
\cf4 17\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob got up and lifted his children and his wives on the camels, \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0and he began driving all his herd and all the goods that he had accumulated, the livestock in his possession that he had accumulated in Paddan-aram, to go to Isaac his father in the land of Canaan.\
\cf4 19\cf5 \'a0Now Laban had gone to shear his sheep, and Rachel stole the teraphim statues that belonged to her father. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Moreover, Jacob outwitted Laban the Aramaean, for he had not told him that he was running away. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0And he ran away and crossed the River, he and all he had. Then he headed toward the mountainous region of Gilead. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0On the third day, Laban was told that Jacob had run away. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0So he took his brothers with him and pursued him for a journey of seven days and caught up with him in the mountainous region of Gilead. \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0Then God came to Laban the Aramaean in a dream by night and said to him: \'93Be careful about what you say to Jacob, either good or bad.\'94\
\cf4 25\cf5 \'a0So Laban approached Jacob, as Jacob had pitched his tent in the mountain and Laban had encamped with his brothers in the mountainous region of Gilead. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0Then Laban said to Jacob: \'93What have you done? Why have you resorted to outwitting me and carrying my daughters off like captives taken by the sword? \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0Why did you run away secretly and outwit me and not tell me? If you had told me, I could have sent you away with rejoicing and with songs, with tambourine and with harp. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0But you did not give me a chance to kiss my grandchildren and my daughters. You have acted foolishly. \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0It is in my power to do harm to you, but the God of your father spoke to me last night, saying, \'91Be careful about what you say to Jacob, either good or bad.\'92 \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0Now you have gone because you have been longing to return to the house of your father, but why have you stolen my gods?\'94\
\cf4 31\cf5 \'a0Jacob answered Laban: \'93It was because I was afraid, for I said to myself, \'91You might take your daughters away from me by force.\'92 \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0Anyone with whom you find your gods will not live. Before our brothers, examine what I have, and take what is yours.\'94 But Jacob did not know that Rachel had stolen them. \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0So Laban went into the tent of Jacob and into the tent of Leah and into the tent of the two slave girls, but did not find them. Then he came out of Leah\'92s tent and went into Rachel\'92s tent. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0Meanwhile, Rachel had taken the teraphim statues and put them in the woman\'92s saddle basket of the camel, and she was sitting on them. So Laban searched through the whole tent but did not find them. \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0Then she said to her father: \'93Do not be angry, my lord, because I am not able to get up before you, for the customary thing with women is upon me.\'94 So he searched on carefully but did not find the teraphim statues.\
\cf4 36\cf5 \'a0At that Jacob became angry and began to criticize Laban. Jacob then said to Laban: \'93What is my offense, and for what sin are you hotly pursuing me? \cf4 37\cf5 \'a0Now that you have searched through all my goods, what have you found that belongs to your house? Put it here in front of my brothers and your brothers, and let them decide between the two of us. \cf4 38\cf5 \'a0During these 20 years that I have been with you, your sheep and your goats never miscarried, and I never ate the rams of your flock. \cf4 39\cf5 \'a0I did not bring you any animal torn by wild beasts. I would stand the loss of it myself. Whether the animal was stolen by day or was stolen by night, you would demand compensation from me. \cf4 40\cf5 \'a0By day the heat consumed me, and the cold by night, and sleep would flee from my eyes. \cf4 41\cf5 \'a0This makes 20 years for me in your house. I have served you 14 years for your two daughters and 6 years for your flock, and you kept changing my wages ten times. \cf4 42\cf5 \'a0If the God of my father, the God of Abraham and the One whom Isaac fears, had not been on my side, you would now have sent me away empty-handed. God has seen my affliction and the toil of my hands, and that is why he reproved you last night.\'94\
\cf4 43\cf5 \'a0Then Laban answered Jacob: \'93The daughters are my daughters and the children my children and the flock my flock, and everything you are looking at is mine and my daughters\'92. What can I do today against these or against their children whom they have borne? \cf4 44\cf5 \'a0Now come, let us make a covenant, you and I, and it will serve as a witness between us.\'94 \cf4 45\cf5 \'a0So Jacob took a stone and set it up as a pillar. \cf4 46\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob said to his brothers: \'93Pick up stones!\'94 And they took stones and made a pile. After that they ate there on the pile of stones. \cf4 47\cf5 \'a0And Laban began calling it Jegar-sahadutha, but Jacob called it Galeed.\
\cf4 48\cf5 \'a0Laban then said: \'93This pile of stones is a witness between me and you today.\'94 That is why he named it Galeed, \cf4 49\cf5 \'a0and the Watchtower, for he said: \'93Let Jehovah keep watch between you and me when we are out of each other\'92s sight. \cf4 50\cf5 \'a0If you mistreat my daughters and if you start taking wives in addition to my daughters, though there is no man with us, remember that God will be a witness between you and me.\'94 \cf4 51\cf5 \'a0Laban went on to say to Jacob: \'93Here is this pile of stones, and here is the pillar that I have erected between you and me. \cf4 52\cf5 \'a0This pile of stones is a witness, and the pillar is something that bears witness, that I will not pass beyond this pile of stones to bring harm to you and you will not pass beyond this pile of stones and this pillar to bring harm to me. \cf4 53\cf5 \'a0Let the God of Abraham and the God of Nahor, the God of their father, judge between us.\'94 And Jacob swore by the One whom his father Isaac fears.\
\cf4 54\cf5 \'a0After that Jacob offered a sacrifice in the mountain and invited his brothers to eat bread. So they ate and spent the night in the mountain. \cf4 55\cf5 \'a0However, Laban got up early in the morning and kissed his grandchildren and his daughters and blessed them. Then Laban departed and returned home.\
