\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Jacob then went on his way, and the angels of God met up with him. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0As soon as he saw them, Jacob said: \'93This is the camp of God!\'94 So he named that place Mahanaim.\
\cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Then Jacob sent messengers ahead of him to his brother Esau in the land of Seir, the territory of Edom, \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0and he commanded them: \'93This is what you will say to my lord, to Esau, \'91This is what your servant Jacob says: \'93I have resided with Laban for a long time until now. \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0And I have acquired bulls, donkeys, sheep, and male and female servants, and I send this message to inform my lord, in order to find favor in your eyes.\'94\'92\'94\
\cf4 6\cf5 \'a0In time the messengers returned to Jacob, saying: \'93We met your brother Esau, and he is now on his way to meet you, and there are 400 men with him.\'94 \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0And Jacob became very frightened and anxious. So he divided the people who were with him, as well as the flocks, the cattle, and the camels, into two camps. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0He said: \'93If Esau attacks the one camp, then the other camp will be able to escape.\'94\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0After that Jacob said: \'93O God of my father Abraham and God of my father Isaac, O Jehovah, you who are saying to me, \'91Return to your land and to your relatives, and I will deal well with you,\'92 \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0I am unworthy of all the loyal love and of all the faithfulness that you have shown toward your servant, for with only my staff I crossed this Jordan and now I have become two camps. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0Save me, I pray you, from the hand of my brother Esau, for I am afraid of him that he may come and attack me, as well as the mothers and their children. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0And you have said: \'91I will certainly deal well with you, and I will make your offspring like the grains of sand of the sea, which are too numerous to count.\'92\'94\
\cf4 13\cf5 \'a0And he spent the night there. Then he took some of his possessions as a gift for Esau his brother: \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0200 female goats, 20 male goats, 200 female sheep, 20 rams, \cf4 15\cf5 \'a030 camels nursing their young, 40 cows, 10 bulls, 20 female donkeys and 10 full-grown male donkeys.\
\cf4 16\cf5 \'a0He handed them over to his servants, one drove after another, and he said to his servants: \'93Cross over ahead of me, and you are to set a space between one drove and the next.\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0He also commanded the first one: \'93In case Esau my brother should meet you and ask, \'91To whom do you belong, and where are you going, and to whom do these ahead of you belong?\'92 \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0then you should say, \'91To your servant Jacob. It is a gift sent to my lord, to Esau, and look! he himself is also behind us.\'92\'94 \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0And he commanded also the second, the third, and all those following the droves: \'93According to this word, you are to speak to Esau when you meet him. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0And you should also say, \'91Here is your servant Jacob behind us.\'92\'94 For he said to himself: \'91If I appease him by sending a gift ahead of me, then afterward when I see him, he may give me a kindly reception.\'92 \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0So the gift crossed over ahead of him, but he himself spent the night in the camp.\
\cf4 22\cf5 \'a0Later during that night, he rose and took his two wives and his two female servants and his 11 young sons and crossed over the ford of Jabbok. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0So he took them and brought them across the stream, and he brought over everything else he had.\
\cf4 24\cf5 \'a0Finally Jacob was left by himself. Then a man began to wrestle with him until the dawn broke. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0When he saw that he had not prevailed over him, he touched the socket of his hip; and the socket of Jacob\'92s hip was dislocated during his wrestling with him. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0After that he said: \'93Let me go, for the dawn is breaking.\'94 To this he said: \'93I am not going to let you go until you bless me.\'94 \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0So he said to him: \'93What is your name?\'94 to which he said: \'93Jacob.\'94 \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0Then he said: \'93Your name will no longer be Jacob but Israel, for you have contended with God and with men and you have at last prevailed.\'94 \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0In turn Jacob inquired: \'93Tell me, please, your name.\'94 However, he said: \'93Why is it that you ask my name?\'94 With that he blessed him there. \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0So Jacob named the place Peniel, for he said, \'93I have seen God face-to-face, yet my life was preserved.\'94\
\cf4 31\cf5 \'a0And the sun rose upon him as soon as he passed by Penuel, but he was limping because of his hip. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0That is why to this day the sons of Israel are not accustomed to eat the thigh sinew, which is on the socket of the hip joint, because he touched the socket of Jacob\'92s hip joint by the thigh sinew.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

