\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Jacob continued to dwell in the land of Canaan, where his father had lived as a foreigner.\
\cf4 2\cf5 \'a0This is the history of Jacob.\
When Joseph was 17 years old, the young man was tending the flock with the sons of Bilhah and the sons of Zilpah, the wives of his father. And Joseph brought a bad report about them to their father. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Now Israel loved Joseph more than all his other sons because he was the son of his old age, and he had a special robe made for him. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0When his brothers saw that their father loved him more than all his brothers, they began to hate him, and they could not speak peaceably to him.\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0Later Joseph had a dream and told it to his brothers, and they found further reason to hate him. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0He said to them: \'93Please listen to this dream that I had. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0There we were binding sheaves in the middle of the field when my sheaf got up and stood erect and your sheaves encircled and bowed down to my sheaf.\'94 \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0His brothers said to him: \'93Are you really going to make yourself king over us and dominate us?\'94 So they found another reason to hate him, because of his dreams and what he said.\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0After that he had still another dream, and he related it to his brothers: \'93I have had another dream. This time the sun and the moon and 11 stars were bowing down to me.\'94 \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0Then he related it to his father as well as his brothers, and his father rebuked him and said to him: \'93What is the meaning of this dream of yours? Am I as well as your mother and your brothers really going to come and bow down to the earth to you?\'94 \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0And his brothers grew jealous of him, but his father kept the saying in mind.\
\cf4 12\cf5 \'a0His brothers now went to pasture their father\'92s flock near Shechem. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Israel later said to Joseph: \'93Your brothers are tending flocks near Shechem, are they not? Come, and let me send you to them.\'94 At this he said to him: \'93I am ready!\'94 \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0So he said to him: \'93Go, please, and see whether your brothers are well. See how the flock is, and bring word back to me.\'94 With that he sent him away from the valley of Hebron, and he went on toward Shechem. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Later a man found him as he was wandering in a field. The man asked him: \'93What are you looking for?\'94 \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0To this he said: \'93I am looking for my brothers. Please tell me, where are they tending flocks?\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0The man continued: \'93They have pulled away from here, for I heard them saying, \'91Let us go to Dothan.\'92\'94 So Joseph went after his brothers and found them at Dothan.\
\cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Now they caught sight of him from a distance, and before he reached them, they began plotting against him to put him to death. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0So they said to one another: \'93Look! Here comes that dreamer. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Come, now, let us kill him and pitch him into one of the waterpits, and we will say that a vicious wild animal devoured him. Then let us see what will become of his dreams.\'94 \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0When Reuben heard this, he tried to rescue him from them. So he said: \'93Let us not take his life.\'94 \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0Reuben said to them: \'93Do not shed blood. Throw him into this waterpit in the wilderness, but do not harm him.\'94 His purpose was to rescue him from them in order to return him to his father.\
\cf4 23\cf5 \'a0So as soon as Joseph came to his brothers, they stripped Joseph of his robe, the special robe that he wore, \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0and they took him and threw him into the waterpit. At the time the pit was empty; there was no water in it.\
\cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Then they sat down to eat. When they looked up, there was a caravan of Ishmaelites coming from Gilead. Their camels were carrying labdanum gum, balsam, and resinous bark, and they were on their way down to Egypt. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0At this Judah said to his brothers: \'93What profit would there be if we killed our brother and covered over his blood? \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0Come, now, let us sell him to the Ishmaelites, and do not let our hand be upon him. After all, he is our brother, our flesh.\'94 So they listened to their brother. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0And when the Midianite merchants were passing by, they lifted Joseph up out of the waterpit and sold him to the Ishmaelites for 20 pieces of silver. These men took Joseph into Egypt.\
\cf4 29\cf5 \'a0Later when Reuben returned to the waterpit and saw that Joseph was not in the waterpit, he ripped his garments apart. \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0When he returned to his brothers, he exclaimed: \'93The child is gone! And I\'97what am I going to do?\'94\
\cf4 31\cf5 \'a0So they took Joseph\'92s robe and slaughtered a male goat and dipped the robe in the blood. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0After that they sent the special robe to their father and said: \'93This is what we found. Please examine whether this is your son\'92s robe or not.\'94 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0Then he examined it and exclaimed: \'93It is my son\'92s robe! A vicious wild animal must have devoured him! Joseph is surely torn to pieces!\'94 \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0With that Jacob ripped his garments apart and put sackcloth around his waist and mourned his son for many days. \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0And all his sons and all his daughters kept trying to comfort him, but he kept refusing to take comfort, saying: \'93I will go down into the Grave mourning my son!\'94 And his father continued weeping for him.\
\cf4 36\cf5 \'a0Now the Midianites sold him in Egypt to Potiphar, a court official of Pharaoh and the chief of the guard.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

