\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Now Joseph was taken down to Egypt, and an Egyptian named Potiphar, a court official of Pharaoh and chief of the guard, bought him from the Ishmaelites who had taken him down there. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0But Jehovah was with Joseph. As a result, he became successful and was put over the house of his master, the Egyptian. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0And his master saw that Jehovah was with him and that Jehovah was making everything that he did successful.\
\cf4 4\cf5 \'a0Joseph kept finding favor in his eyes, and he became his personal attendant. So he appointed him over his house, and he put him in charge of all that was his. \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0From the time he appointed him over his house and in charge of all that was his, Jehovah kept blessing the house of the Egyptian because of Joseph, and Jehovah\'92s blessing came to be on all that he had in the house and in the field. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0He eventually left everything that was his in Joseph\'92s care, and he gave no thought to anything except the food he was eating. Moreover, Joseph grew to be well-built and handsome.\
\cf4 7\cf5 \'a0Now after these things, the wife of his master began to cast her eyes on Joseph and say: \'93Lie down with me.\'94 \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0But he refused and said to his master\'92s wife: \'93Here my master does not know what is with me in the house, and he has entrusted everything he has into my care. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0There is no one greater in this house than I am, and he has not withheld from me anything at all except you, because you are his wife. So how could I commit this great badness and actually sin against God?\'94\
\cf4 10\cf5 \'a0So day after day she spoke to Joseph, but he never consented to lie with her or to remain with her. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0But on one of the days when he went into the house to do his work, none of the household servants were in the house. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0Then she grabbed hold of him by his garment and said: \'93Lie down with me!\'94 But he left his garment in her hand and fled outside. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0As soon as she saw that he had left his garment in her hand and had fled outside, \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0she began to cry out to the men of her house and to say to them: \'93Look! He brought to us this Hebrew man to make us a laughingstock. He came to me to lie down with me, but I began to cry out at the top of my voice. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Then as soon as he heard me raising my voice and screaming, he left his garment beside me and fled outside.\'94 \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0After that she laid his garment beside her until his master came to his house.\
\cf4 17\cf5 \'a0Then she told him the same thing, saying: \'93The Hebrew servant whom you brought to us came to me to make me a laughingstock. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0But as soon as I raised my voice and began to scream, he left his garment beside me and fled outside.\'94 \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0As soon as his master heard the words his wife spoke to him, saying: \'93These are the things your servant did to me,\'94 his anger blazed. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0So Joseph\'92s master took him and gave him over to the prison, the place where the prisoners of the king were kept under arrest, and he remained there in the prison.\
\cf4 21\cf5 \'a0But Jehovah continued with Joseph and kept showing loyal love to him and granting him favor in the eyes of the chief officer of the prison. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0So the chief officer of the prison put Joseph in charge of all the prisoners in the prison, and everything that they were doing there, he was the one having it done. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0The chief officer of the prison was looking after absolutely nothing that was in Joseph\'92s care, for Jehovah was with Joseph and Jehovah made whatever he did successful.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

