\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0After these things, the chief cupbearer of the king of Egypt and the chief baker sinned against their lord, the king of Egypt. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0So Pharaoh grew indignant at his two officers, the chief cupbearer and the chief baker, \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0and he committed them to the jail of the house of the chief of the guard, to the place where Joseph was a prisoner. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0Then the chief of the guard assigned Joseph to be with them and to take care of them, and they remained in jail for some time.\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0The cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt, who were confined in the prison, each had a dream on the same night, and each dream had its own interpretation. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0The next morning, when Joseph came in and saw them, they looked dejected. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0So he asked the officers of Pharaoh who were in custody with him in his master\'92s house: \'93Why are your faces gloomy today?\'94 \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0At this they said to him: \'93We each had a dream, but there is no interpreter with us.\'94 Joseph said to them: \'93Do not interpretations belong to God? Relate it to me, please.\'94\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0So the chief cupbearer related his dream to Joseph, saying to him: \'93In my dream, there was a vine before me. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0And on the vine, there were three twigs, and as it was sprouting shoots, it blossomed, and its clusters ripened into grapes. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0And Pharaoh\'92s cup was in my hand, and I took the grapes and squeezed them out into Pharaoh\'92s cup. After that I put the cup in Pharaoh\'92s hand.\'94 \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0Then Joseph said to him: \'93This is its interpretation: The three twigs are three days. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Three days from now, Pharaoh will bring you out, restoring you to your office, and you will put Pharaoh\'92s cup into his hand as you did before when you were his cupbearer. \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0Nevertheless, you must remember me when things go well with you. Please show me loyal love and mention me to Pharaoh, in order to get me out of this place. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0I was, in fact, kidnapped from the land of the Hebrews, and I have not done anything here for which they should put me in prison.\'94\
\cf4 16\cf5 \'a0When the chief baker saw that Joseph had interpreted something good, he said to him: \'93I too was in my dream, and there were three baskets of white bread on my head, \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0and in the top basket, there were all sorts of baked goods for Pharaoh, and there were birds eating them out of the basket on top of my head.\'94 \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Then Joseph answered, \'93This is its interpretation: The three baskets are three days. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0Three days from now, Pharaoh will behead you and will hang you on a stake, and the birds will eat your flesh from you.\'94\
\cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Now the third day was Pharaoh\'92s birthday, and he made a feast for all his servants, and he brought out both the chief cupbearer and the chief baker in the presence of his servants. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0And he returned the chief cupbearer to his post of cupbearer, and he continued to hand the cup to Pharaoh. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0But he hanged the chief baker, just as Joseph had interpreted to them. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0However, the chief cupbearer did not remember Joseph; he kept forgetting him.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

