\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0At the end of two full years, Pharaoh dreamed that he was standing by the Nile River. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0And there, coming up from the river, were seven fine-looking, fat cows, and they were feeding on the Nile grass. \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0There were seven other cows that looked ugly and thin coming up after them from the Nile, and they stood alongside the fat cows by the bank of the Nile. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0Then the ugly, thin cows began to eat up the seven fine-looking, fat cows. At this Pharaoh woke up.\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0Then he went back to sleep and had a second dream. There were seven ears of grain coming up on one stalk, full and choice. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0And growing up after them were seven ears of grain that were thin and scorched by the east wind. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0And the thin ears of grain began to swallow up the seven full and choice ears of grain. At this Pharaoh woke up and realized that it was a dream.\
\cf4 8\cf5 \'a0But in the morning, his spirit became agitated. So he sent for all the magic-practicing priests of Egypt and all her wise men. Pharaoh related his dreams to them, but there was no one who could interpret them for Pharaoh.\
\cf4 9\cf5 \'a0At that the chief cupbearer spoke with Pharaoh, saying: \'93I am confessing my sins today. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0Pharaoh was indignant at his servants. So he committed me to the jail of the house of the chief of the guard, both me and the chief baker. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0After that we each had a dream on the same night. He and I each had a dream with its own interpretation. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0And there with us was a young Hebrew man, a servant of the chief of the guard. When we related them to him, he interpreted for us the meaning of each dream. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0It happened exactly as he had interpreted to us. I was restored to my office, but the other man was hanged.\'94\
\cf4 14\cf5 \'a0So Pharaoh sent for Joseph, and they brought him quickly from the prison. He shaved and changed his clothes and went in to Pharaoh. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Then Pharaoh said to Joseph: \'93I had a dream, but there is no one to interpret it. Now I have heard it said about you that you can hear a dream and interpret it.\'94 \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0At this Joseph answered Pharaoh: \'93I need not be considered! God will speak concerning Pharaoh\'92s welfare.\'94\
\cf4 17\cf5 \'a0Pharaoh went on to say to Joseph: \'93In my dream I was standing on the bank of the Nile River. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0And there, coming up from the Nile, were seven fine-looking, fat cows, and they began to feed on the Nile grass. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0And there were seven other cows coming up after them, poor and very bad-looking and thin. I have never seen such bad-looking cows in all the land of Egypt. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0And the skinny, bad cows began to eat up the first seven fat cows. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0But when they had consumed them, no one could have known that they had done so, since their appearance was just as bad as at the start. At that I woke up.\
\cf4 22\cf5 \'a0\'93After that I saw in my dream seven ears of grain coming up on one stalk, full and choice. \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0Growing up after them were seven ears of shriveled grain, thin and scorched by the east wind. \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0Then the thin ears of grain began to swallow up the seven choice ears of grain. So I told it to the magic-practicing priests, but there was no one who could explain it to me.\'94\
\cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Then Joseph said to Pharaoh: \'93The dreams of Pharaoh are one and the same. The true God has told to Pharaoh what He will do. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0The seven good cows are seven years. Likewise, the seven good ears of grain are seven years. The dreams are one and the same. \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0The seven skinny and bad cows that came up after them are seven years, and the seven empty ears of grain, scorched by the east wind, will prove to be seven years of famine. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0This is just as I told to Pharaoh: The true God has caused Pharaoh to see what He will do.\
\cf4 29\cf5 \'a0\'93There are to be seven years of great abundance in all the land of Egypt. \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0But seven years of famine will certainly arise after them, and all the abundance in the land of Egypt will certainly be forgotten, and the famine will exhaust the land. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0And the previous abundance in the land will not be remembered because of the famine afterward, for it will be very severe. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0The dream was given twice to Pharaoh because the matter has been firmly established by the true God, and the true God will soon carry it out.\
\cf4 33\cf5 \'a0\'93So now let Pharaoh look for a man who is discreet and wise and place him over the land of Egypt. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0Let Pharaoh take action and appoint overseers in the land, and he should collect one fifth of the produce of Egypt during the seven years of abundance. \cf4 35\cf5 \'a0And let them collect all the food during these coming good years, and let them stockpile grain under Pharaoh\'92s authority as food to be stored in the cities and safeguarded there. \cf4 36\cf5 \'a0The food should serve as a supply for the land for the seven years of famine that will occur in the land of Egypt, so that the land may not perish in the famine.\'94\
\cf4 37\cf5 \'a0This proposal seemed good to Pharaoh and all his servants. \cf4 38\cf5 \'a0So Pharaoh said to his servants: \'93Can another man be found like this one in whom there is the spirit of God?\'94 \cf4 39\cf5 \'a0Pharaoh then said to Joseph: \'93Since God has caused you to know all of this, there is no one as discreet and wise as you. \cf4 40\cf5 \'a0You will personally be over my house, and all my people will obey you implicitly. Only in my role as king will I be greater than you.\'94 \cf4 41\cf5 \'a0And Pharaoh added to Joseph: \'93See, I am putting you over all the land of Egypt.\'94 \cf4 42\cf5 \'a0Then Pharaoh removed his signet ring from his own hand and put it on Joseph\'92s hand and clothed him with garments of fine linen and placed a necklace of gold around his neck. \cf4 43\cf5 \'a0Moreover, he had him ride in the second chariot of honor that he had, and they would call out ahead of him, 
\f3\i \'93Avr\'e9kh!\'94
\f2\i0  Thus he put him over all the land of Egypt.\
\cf4 44\cf5 \'a0Pharaoh further said to Joseph: \'93I am Pharaoh, but without your authorization, no man may do a single thing in all the land of Egypt.\'94 \cf4 45\cf5 \'a0After that Pharaoh gave Joseph the name Zaphenath-paneah and gave him Asenath the daughter of Potiphera the priest of On as a wife. And Joseph began to oversee the land of Egypt. \cf4 46\cf5 \'a0Joseph was 30 years old when he stood before Pharaoh king of Egypt.\
Then Joseph went out from before Pharaoh and traveled throughout all the land of Egypt. \cf4 47\cf5 \'a0And during the seven years of abundance, the land went on producing plentifully. \cf4 48\cf5 \'a0And he kept collecting all the food of the seven years from the land of Egypt, and he would stockpile the food in the cities. In each city he would store the food from the fields around it. \cf4 49\cf5 \'a0Joseph continued stockpiling grain in very great quantity, like the sand of the sea, until finally they gave up measuring it because it could not be measured.\
\cf4 50\cf5 \'a0Before the year of the famine arrived, two sons were born to Joseph, whom Asenath the daughter of Potiphera the priest of On bore to him. \cf4 51\cf5 \'a0Joseph named the firstborn Manasseh, for he said, \'93God has made me forget all my trouble and all the house of my father.\'94 \cf4 52\cf5 \'a0And he named the second one Ephraim, for he said, \'93God has made me fruitful in the land of my affliction.\'94\
\cf4 53\cf5 \'a0Then the seven years of abundance in the land of Egypt ended, \cf4 54\cf5 \'a0and the seven years of famine began, just as Joseph had said. The famine developed in all the lands, but in all the land of Egypt there was bread. \cf4 55\cf5 \'a0Eventually, all the land of Egypt suffered from the famine, and the people began to cry to Pharaoh for bread. Then Pharaoh said to all the Egyptians: \'93Go to Joseph, and do whatever he tells you.\'94 \cf4 56\cf5 \'a0The famine continued over all the surface of the earth. Then Joseph began to open up all the granaries that were among them and to sell to the Egyptians, as the famine had a strong grip on the land of Egypt. \cf4 57\cf5 \'a0Moreover, people of all the earth came to Egypt to buy from Joseph, because the famine had a strong grip on all the earth.\
