\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0When Jacob learned that there was grain in Egypt, he said to his sons: \'93Why do you just keep looking at one another?\'94 \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0He added: \'93I have heard that there is grain in Egypt. Go down there and buy some for us, so that we may stay alive and not die.\'94 \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0So ten of Joseph\'92s brothers went down to buy grain from Egypt. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0But Jacob did not send Benjamin, Joseph\'92s brother, with his other brothers, for he said: \'93Perhaps a fatal accident may befall him.\'94\
\cf4 5\cf5 \'a0So Israel\'92s sons came along with the others who were coming to buy, because the famine had extended to the land of Canaan. \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0Joseph was the man in authority over the land, and he was the one who sold grain to all the people of the earth. So Joseph\'92s brothers came and bowed low to him with their faces to the ground. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0When Joseph saw his brothers, he immediately recognized them, but he concealed his identity from them. So he spoke harshly with them and said: \'93Where have you come from?\'94 to which they said: \'93From the land of Canaan to buy food.\'94\
\cf4 8\cf5 \'a0Thus Joseph recognized his brothers, but they did not recognize him. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0Joseph immediately remembered the dreams that he had dreamed about them, and he said to them: \'93You are spies! You have come to see the vulnerable areas of the land!\'94 \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0Then they said to him: \'93No, my lord, but your servants have come to buy food. \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0We are all sons of but one man. We are upright men. Your servants do not act as spies.\'94 \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0But he said to them: \'93Not so! You have come to see the vulnerable areas of the land!\'94 \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0At this they said: \'93Your servants are 12 brothers. We are the sons of but one man in the land of Canaan, and the youngest is now with our father, whereas the other one is no more.\'94\
\cf4 14\cf5 \'a0However, Joseph said to them: \'93It is just as I said to you\'97\'91You are spies!\'92 \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0By this you will be tested: As surely as Pharaoh lives, you will not leave this place until your youngest brother comes here. \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0Send one of you to bring your brother while you remain in bondage. In this way, your words may be tested out to see if you are telling the truth. And if not, then, as surely as Pharaoh lives, you are spies.\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0With that he put them together in custody for three days.\
\cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Joseph said to them on the third day: \'93Do this and live, for I fear God. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0If you are upright, let one of your brothers remain in bondage in your house of custody, but the rest of you may go and take grain to alleviate the famine in your households. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0Then bring your youngest brother to me, so that your words will be found trustworthy and you will not die.\'94 And they did so.\
\cf4 21\cf5 \'a0And they said to one another: \'93We are surely being punished on account of our brother, because we saw his distress when he begged us to show compassion, but we did not listen. That is why this distress has come upon us.\'94 \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0Then Reuben answered them: \'93Did I not say to you, \'91Do not sin against the child,\'92 but you would not listen? Now his blood is certainly being asked back.\'94 \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0But they did not know that Joseph understood, for there was an interpreter between them. \cf4 24\cf5 \'a0So he turned away from them and began to weep. When he returned and spoke to them again, he took Simeon from them and bound him before their eyes. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Joseph then gave the command to fill up their bags with grain and to return each man\'92s money to his own sack and to give them provisions for the journey. This was done for them.\
\cf4 26\cf5 \'a0So they loaded their grain on their donkeys and left from there. \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0When one of them opened his sack to give fodder to his donkey at the lodging place, he saw his money there in the mouth of his bag. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0At that he said to his brothers: \'93My money has been returned, and now here it is in my bag!\'94 Then their hearts sank, and trembling, they turned to one another and said: \'93What is this that God has done to us?\'94\
\cf4 29\cf5 \'a0When they came to Jacob their father in the land of Canaan, they told him all the things that had befallen them, saying: \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0\'93The man who is the lord of the country spoke harshly with us and accused us of spying on the country. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0But we said to him, \'91We are upright men. We are not spies. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0We are 12 brothers, the sons of our father. One is no more, and the youngest is now with our father in the land of Canaan.\'92 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0But the man who is the lord of the country said to us, \'91By this I will know that you are upright: Leave one of your brothers with me. Then take something to alleviate the famine in your households and go. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0And bring your youngest brother to me, so that I may know that you are not spies but upright men. I will then give your brother back to you, and you may carry on trade in the land.\'92\'94\
\cf4 35\cf5 \'a0As they were emptying their sacks, here was each one\'92s bag of money in his sack. When they and their father saw their bags of money, they became afraid. \cf4 36\cf5 \'a0Jacob their father exclaimed to them: \'93It is I you have bereaved! Joseph is no more, and Simeon is no more, and you are going to take Benjamin! It is upon me that all these things have come!\'94 \cf4 37\cf5 \'a0But Reuben said to his father: \'93You may put to death my own two sons if I do not bring him back to you. Give him over to my care, and I will return him to you.\'94 \cf4 38\cf5 \'a0However, he said: \'93My son will not go down with you, because his brother is dead and he alone is left. If a fatal accident should befall him on the journey you would make, then you would certainly bring down my gray hairs to the Grave in grief.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

