\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Now the famine was severe in the land. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0So when they had finished eating the grain they had brought from Egypt, their father said to them: \'93Return and buy a little food for us.\'94 \cf4 3\cf5 \'a0Then Judah said to him: \'93The man clearly warned us, \'91You must not see my face again unless your brother is with you.\'92 \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0If you send our brother with us, we will go down and buy food for you. \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0But if you do not send him, we will not go down, for the man said to us, \'91You must not see my face again unless your brother is with you.\'92\'94 \cf4 6\cf5 \'a0And Israel asked: \'93Why did you have to bring this trouble on me by telling the man that you had another brother?\'94 \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0They replied: \'93The man directly inquired concerning us and our relatives, saying, \'91Is your father still alive? Do you have another brother?\'92 and we told him these facts. How could we possibly know that he would say, \'91Bring your brother down\'92?\'94\
\cf4 8\cf5 \'a0Judah then urged Israel his father: \'93Send the boy with me, and let us go on our way so that we may live and not die\'97we and you and our children. \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0I will be a guarantee for his safety. You may hold me responsible. If I fail to return him to you and present him to you, I will have sinned against you for all time. \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0But if we had not delayed, we could have been there and back twice by now.\'94\
\cf4 11\cf5 \'a0So Israel their father said to them: \'93If it must be so, then do this: Take the finest products of the land in your bags and carry them down to the man as a gift: a little balsam, a little honey, labdanum, resinous bark, pistachio nuts, and almonds. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0Take double the money with you; and also take back the money that was returned in the mouth of your bags. Maybe it was a mistake. \cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Take your brother and go, return to the man. \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0May God Almighty grant you pity from the man, so that he may release to you your other brother and Benjamin. But as for me, if I must be bereaved, I will be bereaved!\'94\
\cf4 15\cf5 \'a0So the men took this gift, and they took double the money in their hand and Benjamin. Then they rose and went on their way down to Egypt and again stood before Joseph. \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0When Joseph saw Benjamin with them, he at once said to the man who was over his house: \'93Take the men to the house and slaughter animals and prepare the meal, for the men are to eat with me at noon.\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0Immediately the man did just as Joseph had said, and he took them to Joseph\'92s house. \cf4 18\cf5 \'a0But the men became afraid when they were taken to Joseph\'92s house, and they began to say: \'93It is because of the money that was returned in our bags the last time that we are being brought here. Now they will attack us and make us slaves and take our donkeys!\'94\
\cf4 19\cf5 \'a0So they approached the man who was over Joseph\'92s house and spoke to him at the entrance of the house. \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0They said: \'93Pardon us, my lord! We did come down the first time to buy food. \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0But when we arrived at our lodging place and began opening our bags, why, here was the money of each one in the mouth of his bag, our money in full weight. So we would like to return it personally. \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0And we have brought more money to buy food. We do not know who placed our money in our bags.\'94 \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0Then he said: \'93It is all right. Do not be afraid. Your God and the God of your father put treasure in your bags. Your money came first to me.\'94 After that he brought out Simeon to them.\
\cf4 24\cf5 \'a0Then the man brought them into Joseph\'92s house and gave them water for washing their feet, and he gave fodder for their donkeys. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0And they prepared the gift for Joseph\'92s coming at noon, for they had heard that they were going to eat a meal there. \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0When Joseph went into the house, they brought their gift to him into the house and prostrated themselves to him to the ground. \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0After this he inquired about their welfare and said: \'93How is your aged father of whom you have spoken? Is he still alive?\'94 \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0To this they said: \'93Your servant our father is well. He is still alive.\'94 Then they bowed down and prostrated themselves.\
\cf4 29\cf5 \'a0When he looked up and saw Benjamin his brother, the son of his mother, he said: \'93Is this your brother, the youngest one of whom you have spoken to me?\'94 He added: \'93May God show you his favor, my son.\'94 \cf4 30\cf5 \'a0Joseph then hurried out, because he was overcome with emotion for his brother, and he looked for a place to weep. So he went into a private room and gave way to tears there. \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0After that he washed his face and went out, now in control of himself, and he said: \'93Serve the meal.\'94 \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0They served him by himself and them by themselves, and the Egyptians with him ate by themselves, for the Egyptians could not eat a meal with the Hebrews, because that is a detestable thing to the Egyptians.\
\cf4 33\cf5 \'a0The brothers were seated before him, the firstborn according to his right as firstborn and the youngest according to his youth, and they kept looking at one another in amazement. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0He kept sending portions of food from his table to theirs, but he increased Benjamin\'92s portion five times the size of the portions of all the others. So they continued banqueting and drinking with him to the full.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

