\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf4 1\cf5 \'a0Later he commanded the man who was over his house: \'93Fill the bags of the men with as much food as they can carry, and place the money of each one in the mouth of his bag. \cf4 2\cf5 \'a0But you must place my cup, the silver cup, in the mouth of the bag of the youngest, along with the money for his grain.\'94 So he did as Joseph had instructed.\
\cf4 3\cf5 \'a0In the morning when it had become light, the men were sent away with their donkeys. \cf4 4\cf5 \'a0They had not gone far from the city when Joseph said to the man who was over his house: \'93Get up! Chase after the men! When you overtake them, say to them, \'91Why have you repaid bad for good? \cf4 5\cf5 \'a0Is not this what my master drinks from and uses to read omens expertly? It is a wicked thing you have done.\'92\'94\
\cf4 6\cf5 \'a0So he overtook them and spoke these words to them. \cf4 7\cf5 \'a0But they said to him: \'93Why does my lord say such a thing? It is unthinkable that your servants would do anything like this. \cf4 8\cf5 \'a0Why, the money that we found in the mouth of our bags we brought back to you from the land of Canaan. How, then, could we steal silver or gold from the house of your master? \cf4 9\cf5 \'a0If it is found with one of your slaves, let him die, and the rest of us will also become slaves to my master.\'94 \cf4 10\cf5 \'a0So he said: \'93Let it be as you say: The one with whom it is found will become my slave, but the rest of you will be innocent.\'94 \cf4 11\cf5 \'a0With that each one quickly lowered his bag to the ground and opened it. \cf4 12\cf5 \'a0He searched carefully, starting with the oldest and finishing with the youngest. Finally the cup was found in Benjamin\'92s bag.\
\cf4 13\cf5 \'a0Then they ripped their garments apart, and each of them lifted his load back onto his donkey and returned to the city. \cf4 14\cf5 \'a0When Judah and his brothers went into Joseph\'92s house, he was still there; and they fell to the ground before him. \cf4 15\cf5 \'a0Joseph said to them: \'93What is this deed that you have done? Did you not know that a man like me can expertly read omens?\'94 \cf4 16\cf5 \'a0At this Judah replied: \'93What can we say to my master? What can we speak? And how can we prove ourselves righteous? The true God has found out the error of your slaves. We are now slaves to my master, both we and the one in whose hand the cup was found!\'94 \cf4 17\cf5 \'a0However, he said: \'93It is unthinkable for me to do this! The man in whose hand the cup was found is the one who will become a slave to me. As for the rest of you, go up in peace to your father.\'94\
\cf4 18\cf5 \'a0Judah now approached him and said: \'93I beg you, my master, please let your slave speak a word in my master\'92s ears, and do not become angry with your slave, for you are like Pharaoh himself. \cf4 19\cf5 \'a0My master asked his slaves, \'91Do you have a father or a brother?\'92 \cf4 20\cf5 \'a0So we said to my master, \'91We do have an aged father and a child of his old age, the youngest. But his brother is dead, so he is the only remaining son of his mother, and his father loves him.\'92 \cf4 21\cf5 \'a0After that you said to your slaves, \'91Bring him down to me so that I may see him.\'92 \cf4 22\cf5 \'a0But we said to my master, \'91The boy is not able to leave his father. If he did leave him, his father would certainly die.\'92 \cf4 23\cf5 \'a0Then you said to your slaves, \'91Unless your youngest brother comes down with you, you may not see my face anymore.\'92\
\cf4 24\cf5 \'a0\'93So we went up to your slave my father and told him the words of my master. \cf4 25\cf5 \'a0Later our father said, \'91Return and buy a little food for us.\'92 \cf4 26\cf5 \'a0But we said, \'91We are not able to go down. If our youngest brother is with us we will go down, for we cannot see the man\'92s face unless our youngest brother is with us.\'92 \cf4 27\cf5 \'a0Then your slave my father said to us, \'91You well know that my wife bore but two sons to me. \cf4 28\cf5 \'a0But one of them left me and I said: \'93He must surely have been torn to pieces!\'94 and I have not seen him until now. \cf4 29\cf5 \'a0If you were to take this one also out of my sight and a fatal accident were to befall him, you would certainly bring down my gray hairs to the Grave with calamity.\'92\
\cf4 30\cf5 \'a0\'93And now if I return to your slave my father without the boy along with us, since his own life is bound up with this one\'92s life, \cf4 31\cf5 \'a0then as soon as he sees that the boy is not there, he will die, and your slaves will indeed bring down the gray hairs of your slave our father to the Grave in grief. \cf4 32\cf5 \'a0Your slave gave a guarantee to my father for the boy, saying, \'91If I fail to bring him back to you, then I will have sinned against my father forever.\'92 \cf4 33\cf5 \'a0So now, please, let your slave stay instead of the boy as my master\'92s slave, in order that the boy may return with his brothers. \cf4 34\cf5 \'a0How can I return to my father without the boy along with me? I could not bear looking on when this calamity befalls my father!\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi576\qc\partightenfactor0

